tories examines the creative output of the L.A. Rebellion, contextualizing the group's film practices and offering sustained analyses of the wide range of works, with particular attention to newly discovered films and lesser-known filmmakers. Based on extensive archival work and preservation, this collection includes a complete filmography of the movement, over 100 illustrations (most of which are previously unpublished), and a bibliography of primary and secondary materials. This is an indispensible sourcebook for scholars and enthusiasts, establishing the key role played by the L.A. Rebellion within the histories of cinema, Black visual culture, and postwar art in Los Angeles.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAfrican American motion picture producers and directorszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aExperimental filmszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndependent filmmakerszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 0aIndependent filmszCaliforniazLos AngelesxHistoryy20th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Film & Video / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a20th century american film.  aafrican american filmmakers.  aafrican filmmakers.  aalternative film.  aamerican cinema.  aarchival work.  abilly woodberry.  ablack cinema.  ablack experience.  ablack visual culture.  acaribbean filmmakers.  acharles burnett.  acinema.  acritical analysis.  afilm and television.  afilm studies.  afilmography.  ahaile gerima.  ahollywood.  ajamaa fanaka.  ajulie dash.  ala rebellion.  amovie theory.  anew black cinema.  apolitical.  apostwar art.  arebellion.  aucla.  auniversity of california los angeles.  avideo artists.  azeinabu irene davis.1 aClyde, Taylor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aField